\b \cf2 \cb3 Nenbutsu practice
\f2\b0 \cf0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\i \cf2 \cb3 Angama
\i0  shares its mainland Japanese origin with Okinawa's {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eisa_(dance)"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Eis\uc0\u257 }}. The songs to which people dance are called {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nenbutsu"}}{\fldrslt 
\i \cf5 \cb3 nenbutsu}} songs. According to the genealogy of the San'y\uc0\u333  lineage, nenbutsu practice was brought from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryukyu_Kingdom"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Ry\uc0\u363 ky\u363 }} in 1657 when Yaeyama's samurai leader {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Miyara_Ch%C5%8Dj%C5%AB&action=edit&redlink=1"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \cb3 Miyara Ch\uc0\u333 j\u363 }} traveled to Okinawa to pay tribute. It is known from other sources that by that time nenbutsu practice had spread to the capital Shuri\'96Naha region of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Okinawa_Island"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Okinawa Island}}. There were at least two traditions of nenbutsu practice. One was started in the 1600s by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Taich%C5%AB&action=edit&redlink=1"}}{\fldrslt \cf6 \cb3 Taich\uc0\u363 }} (1552\'961639), a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C5%8Ddo-sh%C5%AB"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 J\uc0\u333 do sect}} monk from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutsu_Province"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Mutsu Province}}, and was carried on by his followers in Kakinohana, Naha. The other was performed by the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Chondar%C4%81&action=edit&redlink=1"}}{\fldrslt 
\i \cf6 \cb3 Chondar\uc0\u257 }}, a Shuri-based group of puppeteers, who also had mainland Japanese roots. Folklorist Shinj\uc0\u333  Toshio argued that what Miyara Ch\u333 j\u363  learned must have been Taich\u363 's one.Sakai Masako, a researcher on folk music, questioned Shinj\u333 's theory. Pointing out that Yaeyama has a larger repository of nenbutsu songs than Okinawa, she presumed multiple origins of nenbutsu songs.It was considered taboo to sing nenbutsu songs out of season.\cf2 \cb1 \
