\i angama
\i0  traditions can be divided into two groups: one is performed by the four samurai communities of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ishigaki_Island"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \cb3 Ishigaki Island}} and the other is of commoners in rural communities and remote islands. He argued that the latter had better preserved its traditional way. In the samurai communities of Ishigaki, a group of people with drums (
\i taiko
\i0 ) and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanshin"}}{\fldrslt 
\i \cf5 \cb3 sanshin}} parades around houses of each village. They enter a house that is surrounded by a larger number of spectators. Once everyone sits, 
\i Uya nu Ugun
\i0  (
\f1 \'d3\'48\'a4\'ce\'d3\'f9\'b6\'f7
\f0 , or Nz\uc0\u333  Nenbutsu 
\f1 \'9f\'6f\'ca\'69\'c4\'ee\'81\'96
\f0 ) was sung to mark the beginning, and dancers clap with the beat. Dances and songs alternate with question and answer, in which two masked character 
\i Ushumai
\i0  (old man) and 
\i Nmi
\i0  (old woman) represent ancestral spirits and answer in a humorous way to questions about the afterlife asked by villagers. Kishaba noted that what distinguished samurai's 
\i angama
\i0  from the rural one was that the former was an indoor performance.\cf2 \cb1 \
\cf2 \cb3 In rural communities, 
\i angama
\i0  dances are performed in the garden. A group of people forms a circle. In the center people sing and play drums, flutes, gongs and 
